So like. I have tics. We're not sure why. I meet tourettes criteria but I haven't bothered to get diagnosed. Sometimes I just have to squeal or scream while my body does a funky chicken seizure like I'm releasing ghosts from my blood and we've all just accepted this.

Genuinely shocked at how my husband and girlfriend put up with my nonsense every day. Just accepting my OCD laundry pile that isn't "ready yet" and the loud mouth noises I compulsively make for no reason. Encouraging me when I get excited about fics. They are the real ones tbh.

My girlfriend, showing me cute sneakers: look at these

Me: I love them. Very 90s. I want to look like the interior of a taco bell from 1996 every day of my life.

My girlfriend: ... 

Me: 🙃🙃🙃
Oh. My 3 year old was sleeping walking last night. At like 4 am. Whispering nonsense and standing around for like an hour. Terrifying. Creepy. Children are literally the scariest.

Writing is as much a compulsive thing for me as it is a venue for processing emotions that are too big to carry. Letting the narrative shoulder those burdens for a while can be really clarifying. Anyway, I don't why I'm rambling about all this. I miss my dad. But that's okay. :)

Loss is weird. I noticed that it makes people feel and do strange things. You can be fine one second and then a wreck the next. But even now, years later, one thing stays consistent. It's always the little things that break me. Like suddenly hearing a song dad liked or a scent.

My father in law passed away 3 years ago from a stroke while I was about 7 months pregnant with his first grandchild. I think about all of those missed moments, what it was like to both sit in the hospital and watch someone fade and to have someone ripped away from me instantly.

It's especially funny timing. I didn't really think about it when I started working on this fic but now the timing of what I'm writing and what time of year it is is hitting me. In 11 days it'll be ten years since my dad passed away. very suddenly. He was 41. Pulmonary embolism.

Writing about grief and loss is always such a surreal experience because somehow it's one of the only times I'm able, as a thought exercise, to separate myself from what those feelings were like and look at them objectively.

I think re-entering fandom for the first time in years as I was swiftly closing in on thirty made me look at things differently. Now I find that I write the things that I *want*. Stories I can't find that hit the notes that make me happy and I feel like my work is better for it.

Something I've noticed about what urges me to write fic in any given fandom or for any given piece of media is that... It all depends on how satisfied I am with what content already exists. I didn't used to be like that. I used to just write fic for the sake of. Mostly pwp, too.

My own experiences and connecting with other people who understand. I just want to say Thank you, again, from the bottom of my heart for connecting with Gratitude. With a narrative focused on queerness and mental health. With something so personal. Y'all amaze me. So much. ily.

I have been writing fanfiction since we were all still in emailing groups and I've been through the ringer over the years. Fandom has been a big part of my self discovery journey and my self acceptance of who I am as a queer person. Fiction has been a powerful tool for analyzing

From people who felt seen, represented, understood, and moved by it had such an insane emotional impact on me and I am so fucking grateful for the experience of getting to share that with people. Fandom is a wild place where ymmv but this has been my most positive experience ever

The themes in Gratitude of mental health and intersections with queerness are so personal and important to me. That story has a lot of my own heart wrapped up in it and is the kind of story I want to write when I finally tackle original fiction again. The comments I got...

@DionyFairburn I feel like ditching the habit of "the x male" correlates strongly with my coming to terms with my own transness. USE MY NAME. RAHJJHBDKSKAN.

Be lazy. It's okay. There's nothing wrong with using names or pronouns in place of three word descriptors that only serve to make sentences longer and ultimately more clunky.

And just to be clear: If you do this *that's okay* and you're not a bad writer.

/end ramble

Here's one with two male characters for another example.

"The blonde male didn't like the way the other looked at him."

"Jack didn't like the way Graham looked at him."

Or

"Jack didn't like the way he was being looked at."

Context will do the work for you.

Here's an example of what I mean when I say it'll improve your narrative flow.

"Things weren't looking good for the blonde male."

"Things weren't looking good for Jack."

The use of the characters name makes the sentence feel more urgent. It carries a different weight.

If we already know the character is, let's say, blonde, male, and his name is Jack. You do not need to refer to Jack as "the blonde male". Your sentences will simply flow better if you ditch this habit. It was so prevalent for such a long time in M/M Slash fic. I did it too.

I am not saying that there's never a reason to refer to a character this way but generally you only need to for throwaway extras that don't have names. I promise you, your narrative flow will work better over all if you just use names and pronouns. Context does the work for you.

Pointless pet peeve: "the [insert adjective] [insert gender]" for main characters/characters that are well established and have names. Just... Just use the character's name. Please. I'm begging you. 😭

No complaints here. I'll be sticking with it. It's a better story, better culture, and a better game over all. I have some WoW related hangups and nervousness every time I queue for a group, and every time I'm pleasantly surprised at how much it doesn't turn into a toxic disaster

It feels thoughtful and player focused. I had no idea how much better an MMO experience could be. Even in just 3 weeks of playing, the difference is shockingly apparent and really refreshing. Now if only the ad targeting system was a little more intuitive. Lol. But honestly...

In my WoW days I got called slurs and had all kinds of whacky gamerbro abuse spewed my way over the years with no consequence from other players or the company itself (not shocking all things considered now) whatsoever. The culture is different. The game design is better.

The report system for ToS violations is serious and I saw someone literally get banned within 20 minutes for spewing pro Trump rhetoric/bigotry in chat. And that was after everyone collectively told him he'd joined the wrong gaming community to try and pull that shit.

It turned into a big old joke between the healer and the tank. They turned the frustration into humor and we just kept going with better communication. In my 13 years of playing WoW, never have I ever encountered anything like that outside of my IRL friends/guildmates.

Whereas FFXIV has literally designed their game in a way that rewards everyone for helping newer players and discourages number crunching. I've been in dungeons where the tank was being a little greedy with pulling ads and wiped us multiple times, but instead of jumping ship...

That toxic behavior was still rife within the global raiding community. I've been kicked from raids for not doing "enough damage" aftering being told to engage with the mechanics instead of the boss so we wouldn't wipe. There was no reward for being patient or helpful.

Didn't have hundreds of hours to devote to raiding. When I started WoW it was on a PVP server, where basically, being a jerk to other players was *rewarded*. Literally, the design of the game itself made for a more hostile environment and even when they did away with PVP servers

I used to get harassed in WoW if I wasn't the most efficient player. If you didn't know what to do, people weren't understanding or helpful. If you wiped in raids/dungeons, chances were, everyone would just jump ship and say fuck it. And good luck seeing endgame content if you...

So about three weeks ago I started playing FFXIV because well... I'm never touching WoW again for obvious reasons. I played WoW for 13 years and while I loved a lot of things about it, I never realized until now just how toxic the game was *by design*. It's been mind blowing.

Thinking about writing is part of writing. I wish that was more normalized. Productivity and creativity are not intrinsically tied together. And productivity is not just your word count.

Take it easy and so long as I think about my projects at least a little bit during the day, I've done something to further the story. Because beating myself up for not hitting a word count and only thinking about a scene or finding mood music or scrolling pintrest only ever...

It's all writing. Writing is more than just words on paper. It's immersive and sometimes to write we need to immerse ourselves in enjoying the other parts of writing that aren't hammering out a word count. One of the best habit changes I've made as a writer was to just...

And really focus on getting pumped to work on my story. Whether that means listening to music and envisioning scenes over and over in my head that I may or may not write or doing weird research, or even if I open my doc and write a single new sentence only to walk away...

Really force myself to sit down and hit a certain minimum word count every day. No matter how hard I tried. And being told to throw that piece of advice out and change the way I think about my creative process as a whole has allowed me to take undo pressure off myself...

Mood boards and playlists is part of writing. Opening your document, staring at it, and then closing it again is also writing. All effort you put toward creating your story is part of the writing process and it's all valid. And that resonated with me. I could never...

A piece of writing advice I read years ago, I think during NaNo, that still sticks with me even now is that, writing isn't just the act of putting words to paper. Holding yourself to that is counter productive to creativity. Thinking about your story is writing, creating...

I thought about all the things that could happen and how it would effect my son. Tornados never used to scare me. They were just a force of nature you dealt with. Just like hurricanes when I lived in Florida. But holding my son, thinking about how it would effect him...

Staying calm was incredibly difficult as I got him out of the crib. We went down into the bathroom in our sub level with our dogs and cats. Crowded in. Sang baby beluga, and then the update came. The tornado was three stoplights north of our neighborhood.

My cat started to get anxious, yowling at us. And then that all too familiar weather shift set in. The air seemed to get sucked away. It was hard to breathe and incredibly still. Then something heavy dropped out of the sky and hit our roof and I knew. So I ran to grab my son.

I'm very tired.

No one is "A little obsessive compulsive disorder". You can be particular. Just say that and leave mine, and many other's diagnosis out of your mouth. We're tired of it. Tired of not being listened to because of the common misconception that our neuro divergence is helpful.

Like to attribute so many positive things to OCD, we're deeply misunderstood. I'm sick of it. If there's one thing you can delete from your vocabulary right now to help its the phrase "a little OCD" because it's not fair to us and it's not even grammatically correct.

Now it lives on the floor next to my bed so there's room for me and my spouse to sleep. I need it. It needs to be right there. This is all just a fraction of my life with OCD. People with OCD are neuro divergent. We have our own challenges and stigmas. And because typicals...

I'm not going to clean your house. I can't even clean my own. You are not a little OCD. Everyone has things they're particular about. My particularities have the capacity to control my life. It took me four years to break the habit of keeping everything important to me on my bed.

After my son was born I couldn't leave my bedroom, let alone my house without having a panic attack. It has taken over a decade of hard work to get to a place where I can function in a way that doesn't totally alienate people. My behavior is not palatable. It's not quirky.

I haven't been swimming in a natural body of water in 17 years. Time management is my biggest compulsion and ritual. If people around me make me feel like I'm running behind or late I am prone to panic attacks and possibly even lashing out. Therapy has helped me not do that.

In fact they rarely are. I pick my skin and constantly pull my hair. I cannot drink water that doesn't come from a sealed container without panicking because *what if there's something living in it and it grows inside me* it's outside of my control. I don't know what's in the tap

When my friends came over to help me move we had to get rid of hundreds of empty water bottles. I cried and panicked the entire time. I couldn't tell you why, but letting go of that hoard was like losing a limb. We can't choose our compulsions. They're not always helpful.

When I lived alone I couldn't throw away empty water bottles for a year. I was buried in them because my brain told me I had to keep them for some future purpose. Proper recycling or an art project or maybe to reuse them. I don't know but I couldn't. Get. Rid. Of. Them.

I make the bed every day but I cannot look at the dishes. I cannot look at them. There are too many and I cannot look at them. Do not clear away my clutter I will not be able to find things I need without it. Things are exactly where I need them to be. I know where they are.

I live in controlled chaos. That empty water glass will live on my bedside table so I know where it is and I remember to drink water. The pile of clothes next to my bed are not dirty enough to wash, don't pick them up I still want to wear them.

If I never have to see one more typical person say "I'm a little OCD" because they like to keep their space clean and organized I can die happy. You either have OCD or you don't. OCD =/= organized and clean. Many people who suffer with OCD, myself included, are not tidy people.

Because it's all of Yagi. Not pieces, but every bit of him, good, bad, and neutral.

Vulnerability, Yagi has given him something valuable and tangible. It's not a relationship that takes breaks on bad days, but rather is made stronger and more intimate by them. That tangible thing is trust. Thinking about Aizawa kissing Yagi's knobby knuckles and telling him...

His side for even a moment. Thinking about Aizawa's appreciation for Yagi sharing what time he does have to offer. It's a precious resource, limited, and it's not always pleasant. Thinking about Aizawa not minding the unpleasant bits because in all that pain and shared

Not even thinking twice about it. If Yagi is coughing, if he's bleeding, it's still living. It's the days when Yagi can't even cough that Aizawa is uneasy. It's the days when Yagi doesn't hack and reach for a tissue because he's so bone tired that he finds it difficult to leave

Making sure Yagi is comfortable. Thinking about Aizawa folding laundry on his side of the bed while Yagi rests on the other, watching a documentary together in the quiet, low light of early evening. Thinking about Aizawa collecting bloody tissues from the bedside table and...

Aizawa pushing the cart while Yagi braces one hand against the handle and rests the other on his portable oxygen satchel. Thinking about Aizawa moving at Yagi's pace, meandering so it's low stress on his joints. Thinking about Aizawa adjusting the thermostat on bad pain days.

Thinking about Aizawa helping Yagi set out his medications for the day. Thinking about them sitting down together at the dining table, and doing meal planning on Aizawa's tablet while Yagi drinks tea and Aizawa has coffee. Thinking about shopping trips together, arm in arm.
